t is debatable (and often debated).  However, I’ll leave the discussion of whether it’s right to gank Z for another time and place.<br>
<br>
One note:  Brother Z is a well-understood spawn.  Brother Q in South K is not.  For the sake of your fellow monks, leave Brother Q alone.<br>
<br>
Brother Zephyl is one of four spawns in Rathe Mountains.  His alternate spawns, or place-holders, are Hasten Bootstrutter (the gnome for the J-Boots quest), Maldyn the Unkempt, and “a drake.” Killing a PH will get a respawn in 6-8 minutes.  Hasten is somewhere in the low 40s, and the other two mobs are easier kills, so there is no issue with needing firepower to take the placeholders – the amount of horsepower you need for Brother Z is that far above the PHs.  Before you kill Hasten, do an /ooc to see if anyone’s looking to complete the Jboots quest, for courtesy’s sake.  Likewise before killing Bro Z when you get him to spawn.  Note that he’s sometimes tough to make spawn – we’ve made him spawn in under 30 minutes, but sometimes over two hours with no Bro Z.<br>
<br>
You will need 2 groups of mid 50s, or 3 groups of 48-56 to do this fight effectively, easily, and with low risk.  Many say this fight can be done with a single group 55-60, and I fully believe them, but I wrote this from the perspective of a guild of high 40s to low/mid 50s.  And, in any case, a high 50s group likely doesn't need any advice on handling him.<br>
<br>
Brother Z is level 60-62 and is highly magic resistant, with only the Wizard Lure line of spells having any realistic chance of hitting him, so your groups should be melee and healer heavy.  Your main group should consist of a 56+ tank with autoriposte discipline available, two clerics in 50s with complete heal loaded, a backup healer, a shammy for buffs, and ideally another tank in case things go sour (or a necro to feed mana, but that hasn’t proved necessary so far).  The other two groups don’t need any special composition, just figure a healer or 2 in each.  Casters other than wizzies should stick to buffing and providing/controlling pets for melee, and any healer class should save all mana during melee for heals.<br>
<br>
Set up camp in the HG area, at approximately –600, +600.  Have trackers kill the placeholders till Brother Z spawns.  Once spawned, he can be held in place by hailing him.  Prepare for melee by buffing and hasting the main tank heavily, and of course buffing everyone else appropriately, and getting a good mana pool up.  Give Brother Zephyl a 2Hand Blunt weapon, such as a worn or fine steel great staff.  He will equip the staff, and this will eliminate his quad attacks.  He hits hard – in the 200-300 range, and flying kicks for more, so this step is pretty important.  Once everyone is ready, the main tank attacks and activates his autoriposte discipline.  During this startup it is important that NO ONE attack or cast at Bro Z, and that the clerics refrain from healing the main tank.<br>
<br>
After the autoriposte disc runs out, the main tank’s health will start to drop.  The clerics should decide before-hand who will heal first.  The first cleric should start Complete Heal when the tank is about half way down.  The other cleric will wait 5 seconds and cast complete heal after that, and both will continue to chain cast Complete Heal on the main tank.  The third healer’s job is to drop additional heals on the main tank if his health drops to 1 bub while the CHs are firing.<br>
<br>
About 20-25 seconds after the main tank attacks, all other melee start attacking.  Brother Z summons, so be aware of this and stay on the ball.  It will take time to knock his health down.  When he gets to 2 bubbles of health, the wizzies start to nuke.  Note that casters should not try to slow, debuff, or otherwise cast anything other than Lure spells on Brother Z – it’s a waste of time and mana, and may get you summoned.<br>
<br>
Eventually, Bro Z will stop attacking and slowly walk away.  Once you’ve finished him off, let the monk who’s gonna get the robe loot him.  He drops the RoTLC (no-drop), the black headband, a training tunic, the 2Hblunt you gave him, and sometimes some random little item like a rune.<br>
<br>
Congratulations, you’ve just looted a Robe of the Lost Circle!<br>
<br>
Start killing placeholders again, rinse, and repeat.  If you’re gonna do multiples, you may need to wait for your tank’s autoriposte to recycle.<br>
<br>
We’ve also had a monk start the fight with Whirlwind, main tank join 3 seconds later, monk feigns at low health and stays down for a bit to make sure tank keeps agro, and continue as normal.  The key to this fight is having the main assist hold aggro.<br>
<br>
Some may say this strategy is a bit of overkill, and I’m sure doing it a couple times will enable a guild to trim down the necessary bodycount, but for a first time at it this strategy is pretty much foolproof.<br>
<br>
Keyeluke<br>
Disciple of the Lost Circle, Silent Fist Clan<br>
Strange Brew<br>
Druzzil Ro<br>
