[60 Grand Master]  <a href=http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=3700 target=_blank>Syke</a>  (Iksar)<BR></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#cccccc><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub38.ezboard.com/udamudgedeeler.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Damudge Deeler</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Master</span><br>  Posts: 556<br> <font color=#8b1a1a>(11/9/01 8:08:07 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub35.ezboard.com/fmonklybusiness43508frm2.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=618.topic&index=9>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: re</span><hr size=1> So what is Bard &quot;Twisting&quot;? <p><img src=http://damudgedeeler.homestead.com/files/DD_.jpg width=150 height=200></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#778899><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub38.ezboard.com/bmonklybusiness43508.showLocalUserPublicProfile?login=camthorntikwanleep>Camthorn TiKwanLeep</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Young Grasshoppah</span><br>  Posts: 23<br> <font color=#8b1a1a>(11/9/01 9:15:21 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub35.ezboard.com/fmonklybusiness43508frm2.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=618.topic&index=10>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: re</span><hr size=1> Bard Twisting is a strategy to have multiple songs in effect at once. It works like this, hotkey each song, hit the hotkey and wait until the &quot;casting time&quot; is done. This will start the song's effect, which will last for certain minimum duration regardless of what the bard does after that. So, after the casting time has passed, you hit the hotkey again, which stops the character from actively singing, but(and this is the key) does not stop the effect. Since the character is no longer actively singing, you are eligible to start a second song, so you hit a second hotkey and wait its casting time. Now you have the residual effect of the first song and the effect of the second song, while actually only &quot;performing&quot; one song. In this manner skilled bards(often called the poster children for carpal tunnel syndrome) can keep multiple group-effect spells going most of the time. I've heard of bards that can reliably twist three songs making them amazing groupmates in combat. Twist a regen song, a haste song and a mana regen song and watch everyone love you on a raid(except the mob of course <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  )<br>
<br>
<br>
As an example:  (I've never played a bard, but I know a fair bit about this aspect of the class, I just can't remember if a bard's song takes effect immediately or if there is a lead &quot;casting time&quot; like a caster spell. I don't think there is, you get the effect as soon as you start singing. If there is, then stagger the following example adding the casting time to the duration. The basic sequece is still valid though.)<br>
<br>
Imagine twisting two songs, one with a 2 second &quot;casting time&quot; and an 18 second duration, Song X. A second with a 3 second casting time and a 12 second duration, Song Y. I hit a hotkey to start X. Two seconds later I hit it again and stop singing/playing X, BUT the effect has another 16 seconds before it wears off. So I immediately hit the hotkey for Y. Three seconds later I turn that one off and I have 9 seconds before I need to sing it again. I can swap out instruments, start a third song, whatever I want to do.  9 seconds later I start Y again.  At the time I start this, song X has 4 seconds of duration left. I give song Y it's three seconds of intro needed to establish its effect, then turn it off. Just in time to start song X again. <br>
<br>
It should be noted that the effects would of a single song would be continuous if you didn't &quot;turn it off&quot; but since the minimum duration of song X is 18 seconds and the minimum duration of song Y is 12 seconds, you sacrifice the ease of just turning it on and leaving it on for the difficult and tricky timing of turning on and off several songs to keep them ALL in effect continuously.<br>
<br>
The timings are precise, it's a bitch to do, but it's effect is amazing. Imagine a caster being able to chain-cast spells with no recovery time beyond the casting time. Once the little casting time bar is done, all your spells are available again. Bards have it a little rougher because they sometimes have to swap out instruments to twist certain combinations of songs, but it's still an amazing strategy. <br>
<br>
The reason it feels like an exploit to me? Well, the day you can sing &quot;Mary had a Little Lamb&quot; and &quot;Twinkle Twinkle Little Star&quot; at the EXACT same time and have both still be recognizable, I might believe this was intended. Otherwise I will believe it was a facet of the client-server nature of Everquest and things had to have minimum/maximum durations in order to minimize the amount of snycronizing you had to do to keep the world displayed on the client accurate with the world being played out on the server. There might be one in ten million people who can play a song on an instrument while singing an entirely different song. But in Everquest anyone with fast fingers and knowledge of durations of songs can sing/play multiple songs at once. <br>
<br>
I have argued, on developer's corner as well, for a detailed definition of what is and is not an exploit. I feel that players will never get a fair shake as long as Verant gets to make up the rules on the spot. Twisting has been approved as a &quot;Strategy&quot; and the arguement ends there. <br>
<br>
Handing a 2HB weapon to an NPC with the intent of reducing his effectiveness in the upcoming fight? Is that an exploit? Maybe. Are you willing to bet your account and all the time/effort/money you've invested in your characters on it? That's what's at stake if you're wrong.<br>
<br>
Steven  <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#cccccc><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub38.ezboard.com/bmonklybusiness43508.showLocalUserPublicProfile?login=camthorntikwanleep>Camthorn TiKwanLeep</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Young Grasshoppah</span><br>  Posts: 24<br> <font color=#8b1a1a>(11/9/01 9:34:07 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub35.ezboard.com/fmonklybusiness43508frm2.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=618.topic&index=11>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: re</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> I think Camthorn's thoughts are valid and should be appreciated rather than flamed. He is only looking out for the well being of his fellow player and only saying that this is what Verant has done in the past, setting precedent, so to look out. I don't think he is in anyway advocating VI's EULA beyond the point of simply echoing what it states. To come here and call him VI's puppy dog is very much unwarranted. <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
