<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> <br>
After listening to a song, doesn't it effect you for a few seconds afterwards? If you're singing along (assuming not on stage) don't you sing a few extra bars even though it's done? Or if you're dancing to it don't you do a few extra moves before you finish?<br>
<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Certainly, the effect begins to fade, but it's still there for a little bit.  Now if someone starts singing another song immediately, that's a different matter.<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> <br>
The bard isn't singing multiple songs. He sings or hums or strums a bar from a song, and while people are still thinking 'Yeah! Great song! Let's kick some ass!' he does the same with another song.<br>
<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
True, he's technically not singing multiple songs at once. He's only singing one song and the residual effects of the others are still happening.  It's still pretty far-fetched.  Ever been to a dueling pianos concert?  It's wild.  Trying to imagine one person giving that effect blows my mind and it's even harder to suspend disbelief for the game since I['m a trained musician myself.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> <br>
How about the songs that don't require any continual actions from the bard? They're only one shot, or one shot with a duration. What's so unbelievable about someone belloing (DD+stun) at an orc, then screeching horribly at it (fear)? Or singing a DoT song which casts a multi-tick DoT on the target then singing a different song? If you kept singing the same DoT song it would keep overwriting the previous cast and would be pointless.<br>
<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
I won't start in on specific bard songs or combinations of songs. I don't know the class well enough or have enough experience with it to argue specifics.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> <br>
How is any of this exploiting?<br>
<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
In Norrath, by definition, twisting is not exploiting.  I have never said it is. I said that in my opinion, it feels like an exploit because no human(or elf, or half-elf or any of the races of Norrath using the classic definitions of those races) could execute such a thing in a real world scenario.  Am I willing to live with it?  Sure.  Am I willing to do it if I ever play a bard(something I will probably do soon because I like the class, some of my all time favorite RPG characters have been bards)? Sure.  <br>
<br>
Does it feel right?  No.  It feels impossible, it feels like we're abusing the fact that songs have minimum durations.  Sing two bars of a song and have it affect people for six times as long as we sang?  Especially when we're standing right there belting out another song?   Or belting out two, possibly three other songs?  Nope, still lost me.<br>
<br>
You want to argue that bard songs build up some kind of temporary enchantment in a magical sense?  Sure.  I'm ok with that.  But in that case it's the enchantment creating the lasting effect. The bard has moved on.  <br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> <br>
Besides, bards are useless only playing one song. <br>
<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
Not sure I quite agree with this, but having the ability to twist certainly makes them MUCH, MUCH MORE useful.<br>
